{"key":"processedPost-16394087","value":{"id":16394087,"first":16393901,"last":16403560,"when":1339947786,"utime":"06/17/12 06:43 PM","content":"Yes, you can inoculate a grain jar with a syringe, but I'd keep the lid and jar ring in place.&nbsp; Simply unscrew the ring and then squeeze in on it to lift one side of the lid and filter disk about 1/4\" so you can get the needle in and squirt your spores.&nbsp; Of course, a flowhood makes this nearly risk free, but I've done it dozens of times in a glove box when teaching edible mushroom growing at local schools.&nbsp; <br /><br />It's not necessary to squirt spores to more than one place in the grains because as soon as the mycelium starts to grow and get established, you shake the jar to distribute it.&nbsp; Don't shake after inoculation with spores-wait until it's 10% to 20% colonized.<br />RR","title":"Re: Inoculating Grain - The Jar Lid","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}